9 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Regulation of teletypes -- purpose -- administrative messaging --
10 rulemaking. (1) The use of teletypes facilitates communication between jails and detention centers, serving as
11 a tool to assist with bonding defendants held in remote or distant detention locations when physical presence is
12 impractical. This system was established to address logistical challenges, such as large bond transmittals or
13 situations in which local surety bail bond agents are temporarily unavailable. However, teletypes may not be
14 misused as a substitute for maintaining a meaningful and sufficient local presence. This section governs the
15 permitted use of teletypes to ensure efficiency, prevent system abuse, and protect the operational integrity of
16 jails and detention centers.
17 (2) To manage communication system demands effectively, detention centers are authorized to
18 establish and implement their own reasonable limits on the number of teletypes consistent with constitutional
19 rights, operational capacity, and institutional needs.
20 (3) Surety bail bond insurance producer agencies advertising as statewide providers shall maintain
21 enough licensed surety bail bond agents geographically distributed to reasonably support their claimed service
22 area. The ratio must be at least one licensed surety bail bond agent for each geographic area as determined by
23 the attorney general to qualify as a statewide provider. The agencies shall register licensed surety bail bond
24 agents in assigned regions with the attorney general, and the attorney general shall review compliance with this
25 subsection during license applications and renewals. The license application for agencies may include a fee
26 that is commensurate with the costs of administering this section.
27 (4) Jails must log and monitor teletype request from agencies and agents and report excessive or
28 abusive teletype activity to the attorney general. Jails are authorized to limit the number of simultaneous
